[1] Russia: case surge
Date: Fri 18 Jun 2021
Source: BBC [edited]
https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-57511355


Russia is facing a sharp increase in the number of new COVID-19 infections, while at the same time hosting European Championship football matches in its 2nd city.

The mayor of Moscow has spoken of an "explosion" of cases, and authorities say the numbers are close to last year's [2020] peaks. Twenty million people live in Moscow region, and compulsory vaccinations have now been ordered for service sector staff such as catering and public transport.

St Petersburg, which is hosting 6 Euro 2020 games, is facing a steep rise too. Doctors across Russia have seen a 30% increase in cases in the past week, say officials, amid a significant spread in the Delta variant that originated in India.

This need not have happened. Russia was one of the 1st countries to announce the development of a COVID vaccine and mass vaccinations began last December [2020]. But uptake of vaccinations has been poor.

A variety of restrictions have been imposed across Russia's vast territory, including bans on mass gatherings, reduced capacity at entertainment venues, and greater enforcement of face coverings.

Moscow is now seeing infection numbers as high as December last year [2020], and hospital admissions in the capital are up 70% on last week. Some experts have warned the city could run out of COVID beds in 2 or 3 weeks.

The capital's chief COVID doctor, Denis Protsenko, admitted the situation was difficult but said the healthcare system was adapting to the rapidly changing conditions "in a flexible manner." Mayor Sergey Sobyanin stressed that the entire region was "at the crossing of many roads."

"Moscow is suffering the most frightening blows of the epidemic. That's why we need reliable defence against the disease, against thousands of new deaths among Muscovites," he wrote on the city's website.

Under the new defence plan for the service sector, it is now obligatory for state bodies and private businesses to ensure at least 60% of staff in public-facing roles are vaccinated within a month. That includes staff at cafes and restaurants, public transport, all entertainment venues, beauty salons, and gyms.

Russian health experts have been sounding the alarm for months, warning that the more infectious Delta variant would reach Russia eventually and spread rapidly. Russia has not had a national lockdown, and restrictions have always varied regionally.

The official Coronavirus HQ death toll stands at nearly 130 000. But Russia's Rosstat statistics agency said this month [June 2021] that 270 000 people had died of confirmed or suspected COVID-19 by the end of April [2021].

Moscow has had some of Russia's toughest restrictions, including "non-working" weeks to keep public transport numbers down. But experts say that encouraged more mixing in public places.

Russia is one of the 11 host countries, and Sweden play Slovakia at the St Petersburg Arena on Friday [18 Jun 2021] afternoon. Some doctors have voiced concerns that fans from abroad and Russia's regions will be mixing in the city, spreading the Delta variant even faster.

There has been a small cut in the hours for food sales in fan zones. But authorities have to balance the need to revive the economy and tourism with halting a new COVID wave.

Russia has been vaccinating people since the end of last year [2020] with its aptly named Sputnik V. It has developed and registered 2 more vaccines since.

President Putin and other politicians and celebrities went public when they were vaccinated, and yet the numbers have been sluggish. Only 12.8% of Russians had received a single dose by 16 Jun 2021, and 9.9% were fully vaccinated, according to <statistika-vaccinacia.ru>, which collates regional figures.

Those numbers have begun to pick up, but are still far below levels in the US, UK, the rest of Europe, Israel, and elsewhere. One May [2021] opinion poll suggested 40% of Russians would refuse vaccination under any circumstances, and just over 20% said they would only do so if it meant they could not travel abroad.

Sociologist Denis Volkov of the Levada centre, which conducted 5 polls in the past year, believes many Russians appear to have adopted a wait-and-see strategy. He says they may be looking for more information about the safety and effectiveness of Russian vaccines, including from abroad.

"First, people said that they didn't want to get vaccinated because it's a new disease and the vaccine was developed too fast," he said. Then, half said they did not trust COVID numbers: "Some think the figures are underestimated, some that they are overestimated to sell more face masks and disposable gloves."

The authorities want the vaccination campaign to speed up. President Vladimir Putin's spokesman Dmitry Peskov admits the rollout is going badly. But, asked whether Russia could see compulsory vaccinations for the entire population, he said, "This course of action was not considered at present."

Reports from across Russia speak of employees being threatened with suspension from their jobs until they get vaccinated. Hardline leader Ramzan Kadyrov has gone as far as to warn people in the southern republic of Chechnya that the authorities will be "forced to turn to harsh restrictive measures" unless uptake improves.

[Byline: Kateryna Khinkulova]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

[Russia recorded 17 262 coronavirus cases in the past 24 hours, the highest daily number since 1 Feb 2021, the anti-coronavirus crisis center said on Friday [18 Jun 2021]. The total case count has reached 5 281 309 (https://tass.com/society/1304429).

As with the Copa Americana and the upcoming Olympics, large sports events or events of any kind where masses of people gather are high risk, especially when vaccination rates are low, or vaccines not highly effective. - Mod.LK]

