[3A] Bangladesh
Date: Fri 18 Jun 2021 03:27 a.m. BST
Source: The Daily Star [edited]
https://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/news/covid-infection-dhaka-delta-variant-68pc-cases-2113085


An icddr,b [International Centre for Diarrhoeal Disease Research, Bangladesh)] study found 68% of the coronavirus cases in Dhaka city are of the highly transmissible Delta variant.

Between [25 May and 7 Jun 2021], the scientists at icddr,b analysed the genome sequence of 60 samples taken from COVID-19 patients in the capital.

Of those, 41 or more had the Delta variant [B.1.617.2, first detected in India] of the coronavirus, icddr,b officials confirmed. They also found 22 cases of the Beta variant [B.1.351, first detected in South Africa], 2 cases of the [variant first detected in Nigeria], and 3 Alpha variants [N.1.1.7, first detected in the UK].

[The number of samples described above for whole-genome sequencing is confusing. Two or more variants could be detected in some of the 60 samples investigated. Or, the number of the samples investigated could have been 68. - Mod.PKB]

The B.1.617.2 strain, known as the Delta variant, is worrying health officials across the world, as it caused a major health crisis in India.

In an earlier study by the Institute of Epidemiology, Disease Control and Research, 40 of the 50 samples examined turned out to be of the Delta variant.

Of the 40 cases, only 2 were in Dhaka and the rest in Dinajpur, Gaibandha, Bagerhat, Jhenidah, Pirojpur, Chapainawabganj, Gopalganj, and Khulna.

The latest findings indicate the Delta variant has started dominating transmissions in Dhaka city. Experts fear that this has the potential to turn Dhaka's situation as bad as that of Khulna and Rajshahi.

On [8 May 2021], health officials in Bangladesh detected the 1st case of the Delta variant.

In the 24 hours preceding 8:00 a.m. yesterday [17 Jun 2021], 63 people died with COVID-19, up from 60 the day before.

Of those who were reported dead yesterday [17 Jun 2021], 8 died at home, according to a press release from the Directorate General of Health Services (DGHS).

Of those who were reported dead with COVID-19-like symptoms yesterday [17 Jun 2021], at least 5 were in Jhenidah, 34 in Satkhira, 38 in Khulna, and 20 in Chapainawabganj districts.

Many hospitals in Khulna and Rajshahi divisions have been at capacity amid the rising number of COVID-19 patients.

Experts say the number of daily tests was too low to represent the true picture.

"Most of the infected people remain undetected. There must be many unreported deaths in places where the transmission is higher," infectious diseases specialist Prof Ridwanur Rahman told The Daily Star.

Of those reported dead yesterday [17 Jun 2021], the highest 20 were in Khulna division, followed by 13 in Rajshahi, 11 in Chattogram, 10 in Dhaka, 3 in Barishal, and 2 each in Rangpur, Mymensingh, and Sylhet.

At least 3840 people tested positive for COVID-19 while the positivity rate declined to 15.44% from 16.62 the previous day.

Officials in Gopalganj imposed restrictions on movements and outdoor activities in areas under the municipalities of Gopalganj and Moksudpur, and the unions of Latifpur and Kashiani to curb the spread of the virus.

Another 11 districts have enforced the restrictions before. But transmission in most of those areas continues to rise, according to DGHS data.

