Over the last 7 days, 487 970, 20 692, 7490, 14 297, and 11 128 COVID-19 cases were detected in India, Bangladesh, Pakistan, Nepal, and Afghanistan, respectively, compared with 700 473, 14 415, 10 149, 24 751, and 11 088 in the preceding 7 days, revealing the continuation of the sharp decreasing trend in India, Pakistan, and Nepal; a stable trend in Afghanistan; but the continuation of the upward trend in Bangladesh. In Sri Lanka, a declining trend was also seen over the last 7 days when 16 930 cases were detected against 20 290 over the previous 7 days.

The daily case positivity in Bangladesh was above 15% over the last 2 days. Recent sequence data of the virus from samples collected from different parts of the country and recently from the capital city Dhaka revealed the predominance of the Delta variant (previously called B.1.617.2), a variant of concern. The high case positivity of the disease being seen over a period of 2 weeks or so in the country is probably due to community transmission of the variant, which is more transmissible than the Alpha variant. However, the simultaneous presence of the Alpha (B.1.1.7) and Beta variants (B.1.351) was also detected in the country, as indicated in item [1] above.

